  abstract = {{$<$}section class="abstract"{$><$}h2 class="abstractTitle text-title my-1" id="d1103e2"{$>$}Abstract{$<$}/h2{$><$}p{$>$}In the Modern-Era Retrospective Analysis for Research and Applications version 2 (MERRA-2) system the land is forced by replacing the model-generated precipitation with observed precipitation before it reaches the surface. This approach is motivated by the expectation that the resultant improvements in soil moisture will lead to improved land surface latent heating (LH). Here aspects of the MERRA-2 land surface energy budget and 2-m air temperatures {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf1.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} are assessed. For global land annual averages, MERRA-2 appears to overestimate the LH (by 5 W m\textsuperscript{-2}), the sensible heating (by 6 W m\textsuperscript{-2}), and the downwelling shortwave radiation (by 14 W m\textsuperscript{-2}) while underestimating the downwelling and upwelling (absolute) longwave radiation (by 10\textendash 15 W m\textsuperscript{-2} each). These results differ only slightly from those for NASA's previous reanalysis, MERRA. Comparison to various gridded reference datasets over boreal summer (June\textendash August) suggests that MERRA-2 has particularly large positive biases (\&gt;20 W m\textsuperscript{-2}) where LH is energy limited and that these biases are associated with evaporative fraction biases rather than radiation biases. For time series of monthly means during boreal summer, the globally averaged anomaly correlations {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf2.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} with reference data were improved from MERRA to MERRA-2, for LH (from 0.39 to 0.48 vs Global Land Evaporation Amsterdam Model data) and the daily maximum {$<$}em{$>$}T{$<$}/em{$>$}\textsuperscript{2m} (from 0.69 to 0.75 vs Climatic Research Unit data). In regions where {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf4.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} is particularly sensitive to the precipitation corrections (including the central United States, the Sahel, and parts of South Asia), the changes in the {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf5.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf6.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} are relatively large, suggesting that the observed precipitation influenced the {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press"{$><$}img src="jcli-d-17-0121.1-inf7.gif"{$><$}/img{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} performance.{$<$}/p{$><$}/section{$>$}},
